    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>The Ambassador in China (
                        Stuart
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1948v07</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d377</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">377</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1948-10-01T21:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1948-10-01T21:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-10-01T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-10-01T21:00:00-05:00" n="377" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d377">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/10–248: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-10-02T10:00:00+08:00">October 2, 1948—10 a. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 2—1:31 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1815. Gimo with personal staff including Commanders in Chief Navy<note n="49" xml:id="d377fn49">Adm. Kwei Yung-ching.</note> and Air Force,<note n="50" xml:id="d377fn50">Gen. Chou Chih-jou.</note> and Deputy Commander Ground
                        Forces<note n="51" xml:id="d377fn51">Lt. Gen. Sun Li-jen.</note> arrived
                    Peiping September 30. Press carries story arrival Peiping for purpose “comfort
                    North China citizens and armed forces”. Real purpose, as yet unpublicized, is
                    proceed to Mukden in attempt secure compliance Wei Li-huang with Gimo’s orders
                    attack in force westward to relieve Communist pressure on Chinchow, which now in
                    very critical position (our 1807<note n="52" xml:id="d377fn52">September 30, 6
                        p. m., <ref target="#pg_477">p. 477</ref>.</note>). Wei received orders on
                    26th and as of evening 30th had not yet moved forward.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
